"""
MKT Context -- Luke 17-18
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/luke.json

Ch17: Stumbling-blocks and community discipline, mustard-seed faith, unworthy-
  servant parable (slave economy), ten lepers (Samaritan gratitude), kingdom
  debate (entos hymon), Noah and Lot parallels for the Son of Man's day.
Ch18: Persistent widow (Roman court system, unjust judge), Pharisee-and-tax-
  collector (Second Temple prayer postures, justification language), children
  and the kingdom, rich ruler (camel-needle saying, eternal inheritance),
  third passion prediction, Bartimaeus (Jericho, Son of David messianic title).
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge new_data into existing without overwriting any present entry
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
'17': {
'1': '<p>Stumbling blocks (skandala = traps, snares) were a recognized category of moral harm in Jewish ethics. The term skandalon (from the mechanism of a trap) described anything that caused someone to fall into sin. "Things that cause people to stumble are bound to come" (anendeckton estin tou ta skandala m&#275; elthein) frames the saying with inevitability: the world will always contain occasions of stumbling. But this does not reduce the culpability of those who create them. The "woe" (ouai) signals prophetic condemnation of the deliberate or reckless creation of spiritual hazards for others.</p>',
'2': '<p>The millstone image: a mylon onikos is a donkey-driven millstone -- a large (2+ foot diameter) stone turned by an animal, far heavier than the smaller hand-millstone (mylos cheirikos). Being thrown into the sea with such a stone around one\'s neck was a recognized form of drowning-execution in the ancient world (Josephus Ant. 14.450 describes rebels drowned in the Lake of Galilee; the Romans used the practice). The comparison is stark: death by drowning would be preferable to the fate of one who causes a child (or a "little one" = a new or vulnerable disciple) to stumble. The severity establishes the principle: spiritual harm to the vulnerable is among the gravest sins.</p>',
'3': '<p>"Watch yourselves" (prosechete heautois) -- the exhortation to community vigilance, not just individual discipline. The pattern of rebuke and forgiveness follows Matt 18:15-22 (the community discipline passage), though Luke\'s version is briefer and more focused on the repeated forgiveness (seven times, v4). The Qumran community had elaborate rebuke procedures (1QS 5:24-6:1: rebuke must be immediate, in private, and before witnesses before bringing the matter to the assembly). Jesus\' instruction modifies the pattern: the goal is not communal purity but restoration of the brother.</p>',
'4': '<p>"Even if they sin against you seven times in a day and seven times come back to you saying \'I repent,\' you must forgive them" -- the "seven times" reflects Jewish conventions about the limits of forgiveness. In Amos 1-2, God warns nations after three transgressions and then again (four); the implied limit suggests that forgiveness has boundaries. Matthew 18:21-22 has Peter asking if seven times is enough, and Jesus responding "seventy-seven times" or "seventy times seven." Luke\'s "seven times in a day" intensifies the demand: not seven times over a lifetime but seven times in a single day, each time with expressed repentance.</p>',
'5': '<p>The apostles\' request for increased faith ("Increase our faith!") is a response to the demand of vv.3-4 -- they recognize that forgiving a brother seven times in a day exceeds normal human capacity and requires a faith larger than they currently possess. The request prostithei h&#275;min pistin (increase/add to us faith) uses prostithemi, the same word used in Acts for adding converts to the community. Faith here is understood not as intellectual belief but as the enabling resource for radical obedience.</p>',
'6': '<p>The mustard-seed response to the faith-request is paradoxical: even faith as small as a mustard seed (the proverbially smallest seed, cf. 13:19; Mark 4:31) has extraordinary power. "This mulberry tree" (t&#275; sykamiō = the sycamine/mulberry tree, probably the black mulberry, Morus nigra, with very deep roots -- distinguished from the sycamore fig of 19:4) being uprooted and planted in the sea is a deliberately impossible image. The point is not about miraculous tree-transplantation but about the disproportion between the size of faith and the magnitude of its effects: even the smallest genuine faith exceeds the seemingly impossible demand.</p>',
'7': '<p>The parable of the unworthy servant (vv.7-10) is unique to Luke. The social background: servants (douloi = slaves) in the first-century Mediterranean world had no rights and no claim on their master\'s gratitude. After ploughing all day or tending sheep, the slave\'s obligation to serve the evening meal continued -- there was no "thank you for your work" moment when the slave could expect special treatment. This was the legal and social reality: the master\'s acknowledgment of the slave\'s work was entirely discretionary, not obligatory.</p>',
'8': '<p>The master\'s instruction to prepare his dinner while still in work clothes before eating and drinking himself is a description of the normal slave economy, not cruelty. The master\'s table service came before the slave\'s rest -- this was taken for granted in antiquity. The parable is not endorsing slavery as a moral good but using the understood social structure to make a point about discipleship. The "meta tauta" (after these things) indicates the sequence: master first, servant second. The sequence is simply assumed; no elaboration is needed.</p>',
'9': '<p>"Will he thank the servant because he did what he was told to do?" -- the rhetorical question expects the answer "no." Gratitude (charin = grace, favor, thanks) was owed by a slave to a master who treated him well, not the other way around. The master was not in the slave\'s debt for the slave performing his assigned duties. The social logic is inverted from modern expectations, where effort deserves reward. In the slave economy, the default was obligation without gratitude from the master.</p>',
'10': '<p>"So you also, when you have done everything you were told to do, should say, \'We are unworthy servants; we have only done our duty\'" -- the application to disciples is pointed. The Greek achreios (unworthy, useless) is strong: not merely "humble" but "of no special value to the master." The disciples\' obedience (even the extraordinarily demanding obedience of repeated forgiveness) gives them no claim on God\'s gratitude or reward -- it is simply what is expected of those who have been given the Kingdom. This cuts against any theology of merit: even complete obedience does not create a divine debt.</p>',
'11': '<p>"On his way to Jerusalem, Jesus traveled along the border between Samaria and Galilee" -- Luke\'s travel narrative (9:51-19:27) has Jesus moving toward Jerusalem since 9:51. The Samaria-Galilee border region was the mixed territory where Jewish-Samaritan tensions were highest (cf. the Samaritan rejection of 9:52-53). The healing of the ten lepers occurs precisely in this liminal social space, setting up the irony that the returning grateful leper is a Samaritan. The narrative geography underscores the universal reach of Jesus\' healing and the unexpected location of gratitude.</p>',
'12': '<p>Ten lepers who stood at a distance (ap&#333; = from a distance) -- Lev 13:45-46 required lepers to keep a distance from the unaffected population and to call out "Unclean! Unclean!" when anyone approached. The enforced distance of the lepers reflects not just physical health concerns but the social and ritual exclusion that leprosy imposed: they were a group at the margins, having formed their own band of exclusion across the normal Jew-Samaritan social divide (they too could not maintain ethnic distinctions in their shared misery).</p>',
'13': '<p>"Jesus, Master, have pity on us!" -- Epistata (Master) is Luke\'s characteristic Christological title (4:38; 5:5; 8:24, 45; 9:33, 49). The plural call reflects both the desperation of corporate affliction and the solidarity of the excluded group. "Have pity on us" (ele&#275;son h&#275;mas) is the language of Psalm prayer (Ps 4:1; 6:2; 31:9; 86:3) and the Kyrie eleison of the liturgical tradition. Their cry from a distance does not yet involve approach; they call out hoping Jesus will act toward them, not requiring them to violate the distance-protocol first.</p>',
'14': '<p>"Go, show yourselves to the priests" -- the instruction follows Lev 14:2-32 exactly: the cleansed leper must present himself to the priest for examination and the eight-day purification ritual before being declared clean. Jesus sends them before the cleansing has occurred -- the healing happens "as they went" (en t&#333; hypeigein autous = while they were going). The faith required is to set out for the priest before the evidence of healing. The contrast with the unhealed Naaman who almost refused Elisha\'s instruction (2 Kgs 5:11-13) is instructive: these lepers obey immediately.</p>',
'15': '<p>One of them, when he saw he was healed, turned back -- the word hypestrepsas (turned back, returned) is significant: all ten were healed "as they went" toward the priests, but only one turned back. The nine were not ungrateful per se; they were following the instruction Jesus had given. The one who returned made a different choice: he prioritized the source of the healing over the next prescribed step. His return is an act of worship priority over religious compliance.</p>',
'16': '<p>He "threw himself at Jesus\' feet and thanked him -- and he was a Samaritan." The prostration at Jesus\' feet (pesōn epi pros&#333;pon para tous podas autou = falling on his face at his feet) is the posture of worship, not merely social deference. The shock of the narrative: the one who most honored Jesus with gratitude was from the most despised group -- the Samaritan. Luke\'s consistent pattern: the Samaritan hero (10:33), the Samaritan leper (17:16), and the Samaritan evangelization of Acts 8:5-25 together constitute a running Lukan argument for the universality of grace.</p>',
'17': '<p>"Were not all ten cleansed? Where are the other nine?" -- the question (Jesus addresses the crowd, not the Samaritan) is rhetorical: ten were healed, one returned. The proportion of gratitude (1/10 = 10%) among the blessed contrasts with the completeness of the blessing (100% healed). Jesus\' question invites the listeners to notice the disproportion. The nine presumably continued to the priests as instructed -- they were observing Torah. But the Samaritan\'s return demonstrates that something more than Torah-compliance had occurred in his healing: a relationship.</p>',
'18': '<p>"Has no one returned to give praise to God except this foreigner?" -- allogenes (foreigner, of another race) is the technical term used in the temple for those excluded from the inner courts: the inscription on the temple barrier read "Let no foreigner enter within the barrier and wall around the holy place. Whoever is caught doing so will himself be responsible for his ensuing death" (Josephus Ant. 15.417). The foreigner who cannot enter the temple gives God the praise that nine Jewish men who can enter have not given. The irony is complete.</p>',
'19': '<p>"Rise and go; your faith has made you well" -- the formula of healing-through-faith (h&#275; pistis sou ses&#333;ken se = your faith has saved you) appears at the hemorrhaging woman (8:48), the blind man (18:42), and here. The language uses s&#333;z&#333; (save/heal) -- the same word as soteria (salvation). The leper\'s healing already occurred in v.14; what Jesus says to him alone adds a further dimension: the nine were healed (iathr&#275;san = were healed, medical term) but the Samaritan was "saved" (ses&#333;ken = saved, with its full salvific weight). The returning gratitude is itself a component of what salvation means.</p>',
'20': '<p>"The kingdom of God does not come with your careful observation" -- the Pharisees\' question about when the kingdom of God would come reflects the intense eschatological expectation of first-century Judaism: the Zealots expected military liberation, the Essenes expected a divine intervention at a calculated time, the Pharisees debated the conditions for God\'s act (b. Sanhedrin 97b-98a: "The Son of David will come only when the whole world has become either entirely righteous or entirely wicked"). Jesus refuses the observable-sign framework: parateresis (careful observation/watching for signs) is not the mode of the kingdom\'s arrival.</p>',
'21': '<p>"Nor will people say, \'Here it is,\' or \'There it is,\' because the kingdom of God is in your midst" -- the phrase entos hym&#333;n (within you / among you / in your midst) is the most debated expression in Luke. Three interpretations: (1) "within you" = interior/spiritual -- the kingdom is an inner reality (Origen, many mystics); (2) "among you" = present in Jesus himself who stands among them -- the kingdom is present in his person (most modern scholars); (3) "in your grasp/within your reach" = the kingdom is accessible to those who respond. The context (Pharisees asking, Jesus saying they will not see it by external observation) favors interpretation (2): the kingdom is already present in Jesus\' ministry before their eyes, but they are not recognizing it.</p>',
'22': '<p>"The time is coming when you will long to see one of the days of the Son of Man, but you will not see it" -- Jesus shifts from the Pharisees to the disciples. The "days of the Son of Man" is apocalyptic language for the era of the Son of Man\'s visible reign. The disciples\' future longing reflects the post-ascension period: between resurrection and parousia, the community will deeply desire the visible return of Jesus. This longing is not a failure of faith but a mark of genuine love for the absent Lord (cf. Rev 22:20: "Come, Lord Jesus").</p>',
'23': '<p>"People will tell you, \'There he is!\' or \'Here he is!\'" -- false messianic and apocalyptic claims were common in first-century Palestine: Josephus describes several messianic pretenders (the Egyptian prophet, Theudas, the unnamed prophet from outside Jerusalem: Acts 21:38; Ant. 20.97-98, 169-172; War 2.258-265). After the destruction of Jerusalem (70 CE), the messianic speculation intensified. Jesus warns against responding to such claims: "Do not go running off after them." The disciples must not mistake historical catastrophes for the parousia.</p>',
'24': '<p>"For the Son of Man in his day will be like the lightning, which flashes and lights up the sky from one end to the other" -- the comparison of the parousia to lightning clarifies the previous warning about false sightings: lightning does not need to be pointed out; it is unmistakably self-announcing. When the Son of Man actually appears, there will be no question about location or identification -- he will be visible everywhere simultaneously. This is the antidote to "he is here" or "he is there" claims: the real event will be universally self-evident.</p>',
'25': '<p>"But first he must suffer many things and be rejected by this generation" -- the "must" (dei) is Luke\'s divine-necessity marker (2:49; 4:43; 9:22; 13:33; 22:37; 24:7, 26). The passion prediction is inserted into the apocalyptic discourse to insist that the way to the Son of Man\'s glorious arrival runs through rejection and death. The disciples\' expectation of messianic triumph must be re-routed through the cross. "This generation" (t&#275;s geneas taut&#275;s) carries the prophetic weight of covenantal failure: the generation that rejected the prophets and will reject the Son.</p>',
'26': '<p>"Just as it was in the days of Noah, so also will it be in the days of the Son of Man" -- the Noah analogy appears in Matt 24:37-39 and here. Jewish apocalyptic used Noah as the type of the faithful survivor amid universal judgment: 1 Enoch 106-107; Jub. 5:1-11; the Dead Sea Scrolls Noah fragments (4Q534-536). The key element is not immorality but normalcy: they were "eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage" -- ordinary life proceeding without awareness of impending judgment. The point is not that ordinary life is sinful but that absorption in it can make people oblivious to eschatological urgency.</p>',
'27': '<p>The Flood narrative (Gen 6-9) provides the historical backdrop: "the flood came and destroyed them all." Noah (Gen 6:9: "a righteous man, blameless among the people of his time") was saved; the unprepared world perished. The parallel function is preparedness: Noah prepared an ark in obedience to divine warning; the disciples are warned in advance so that they will not be caught unprepared. The flood destroyed all (pantes) -- the universality of judgment contrasts with the particularity of salvation.</p>',
'28': '<p>The Lot analogy is uniquely Lukan among the Synoptics. Lot and the destruction of Sodom (Gen 19) provides the second type. "People were eating and drinking, buying and selling, planting and building" -- the same normalcy as in Noah\'s day. Sodom\'s destruction came as a sudden divine intervention after Lot\'s departure: no observable signs, just the abrupt end of ordinary time. Jewish tradition remembered Lot ambivalently (2 Pet 2:7: "a righteous man"), but his story was unambiguously a type of divine judgment on a civilization that had rejected the divine standard.</p>',
'29': '<p>"But the day Lot left Sodom, fire and sulfur rained down from heaven and destroyed them all" -- the fire and sulfur (pyr kai theion) of Gen 19:24 (LXX: p&#363;r kai theion = fire and sulfur) became a standard image of divine judgment in the OT and NT (Isa 30:33; Ezek 38:22; Rev 14:10; 19:20; 20:10; 21:8). The destruction "destroyed them all" (apōlesen pantes) parallels the flood\'s destruction: both judgments were total, sudden, and without warning for the unprepared.</p>',
'30': '<p>"It will be just like this on the day the Son of Man is revealed" -- apokalupt&#275;tai (is revealed/unveiled) connects the parousia to the apocalyptic tradition of the revealing of the hidden divine figure (cf. Dan 7:13-14; 1 Cor 1:7; 1 Pet 1:7, 13; 4:13; 2 Thess 1:7: "when the Lord Jesus is revealed from heaven"). The Son of Man who is currently hidden (or rejected) will be universally unveiled at his coming. The revelation is not a discovery of something new but the uncovering of what has always been true about Jesus\' identity.</p>',
'31': '<p>"On that day no one who is on the housetop, with possessions inside, should go down to get them" -- the urgency instruction echoes the Olivet Discourse (Mark 13:15; Matt 24:17). The Palestinian house had a flat roof accessible by exterior staircase, where people slept in summer and worked (Acts 10:9: Peter praying on the roof). The instruction is: when the moment comes, do not turn back for material possessions. "Let no one in the field go back for anything" -- field work required going out from the house; the instruction is not to return home. These instructions have a concrete application to the flight from Jerusalem in 70 CE and an eschatological application to the final day.</p>',
'32': '<p>"Remember Lot\'s wife!" -- the briefest warning in the teaching, referencing Gen 19:26 ("Lot\'s wife looked back, and she became a pillar of salt"). The tradition about Lot\'s wife was widely developed in Jewish sources (Wis 10:7: "a pillar of salt stands as a monument to an unbelieving soul"; Josephus Ant. 1.203 says she turned into a pillar of salt "to this day"). Her backward look is interpreted as attachment to what was being left behind: the possessions, the city, the former life. The warning is against the divided heart that looks forward and back simultaneously.</p>',
'33': '<p>"Whoever tries to keep their life will lose it, and whoever loses their life will preserve it" -- this saying appears in multiple forms and contexts throughout the Synoptics (Mark 8:35; Matt 10:39; 16:25; Luke 9:24; John 12:25), suggesting it was a fundamental and often-repeated teaching. The paradox of life-through-death and death-through-self-preservation is the core of the cross-bearing call (9:23). In the eschatological context of the Son of Man\'s coming, the principle applies to the final decision: clinging to earthly life at the decisive moment means ultimate loss.</p>',
'34': '<p>"I tell you, on that night two people will be in one bed; one will be taken and the other left" -- the nighttime setting (night in the Eastern Mediterranean = sleeping time, when people are most caught unprepared) describes the sudden selective nature of the eschatological separation. The "taken" (paralēmphth&#275;setai) and "left" (apheth&#275;setai) have been interpreted variously: taken for judgment (as in Noah\'s flood where the wicked were swept away) or taken for salvation (as in 1 Thess 4:17: "caught up"). Luke\'s parallel with the flood suggests the "taken" may be those overtaken by judgment.</p>',
'35': '<p>"Two women will be grinding grain together; one will be taken and the other left" -- grinding grain was women\'s daily work (Exod 11:5; Num 11:8; Isa 47:2; Matt 24:41). Two women grinding together (at a shared hand mill) represents the most ordinary of domestic scenes -- the contrast with the spectacular eschatological event maximizes the unexpectedness. The separation of those who appear identical in situation and activity underscores that the division is based on inner readiness, not outward circumstance.</p>',
'36': '<p>This verse ("Two men will be in the field; one will be taken and the other left") is present in some manuscripts (following the pattern of Matt 24:40) but absent from the best Lukan manuscripts (P75, Vaticanus, Sinaiticus). It appears to be a harmonizing addition from Matthew\'s version. The standard Lukan text proceeds from v35 to v37 without this verse. Its absence in Luke preserves the two contrasting examples (nighttime bed, daytime grain-grinding) that together cover the range of times and activities.</p>',
'37': '<p>"Where, Lord?" -- the disciples\' question about location is answered with a natural proverb about carrion birds: "Where there is a dead body, there the vultures will gather." The parallel in Matt 24:28 has the same saying. The vultures (or eagles -- aetoi = eagles, but the image suggests vultures circling over a carcass) gathering around a carcass is a self-locating event: the birds do not need to be shown where the carcass is; they are drawn to it naturally. Similarly, the Son of Man\'s coming will be self-evident -- asking "where?" is as unnecessary as asking where the vultures are gathering. The obvious sign locates itself.</p>',
},
'18': {
'1': '<p>The persistent widow parable (vv.1-8) is introduced with its moral before the story: "he told them a parable to show them that they should always pray and not give up." The explicit moral introduction (unusual for Luke) alerts the reader that the parable is analogical rather than allegorical: the judge is not a portrait of God but an extreme contrast that makes the point by kal vachomer (lesser-to-greater). The "always pray and not give up" (proseuchesthai autous dei kai m&#275; enkakein) uses dei (necessity) -- the same divine-necessity word that governs Jesus\' own path -- applying it to the community\'s ongoing prayer.</p>',
'2': '<p>"In a certain town there was a judge who neither feared God nor cared what people thought" -- the two deficiencies define the judge as corrupt. In Jewish ethics, the fear of God was the foundation of impartial justice (Deut 1:17: "Do not show partiality in judging; hear both small and great alike. Do not be afraid of anyone, for judgment belongs to God"). Caring about human reputation was the social check on a judge\'s behavior when fear of God failed. A judge without both constraints was the worst possible official: unchecked by either divine accountability or social shame. The Roman provincial court system of the first century included judges (iudices) who could be corrupt and venal, as documented in Cicero\'s prosecution of Verres.</p>',
'3': '<p>"And there was a widow in that town who kept coming to him with the plea: \'Grant me justice against my adversary.\'" -- widows occupied a specific vulnerable position in the ancient legal system. Without a husband or male guardian (kyrios) to represent them, widows had no standing to pursue legal claims in many ancient courts. The OT repeatedly commands justice for widows (Exod 22:22-24; Deut 10:18; 24:17; Isa 1:17; Jer 7:6; Zech 7:10). The widow\'s repeated coming (&#275;rcheto = imperfect, she kept coming) represents persistent legal pursuit without natural social support. Her adversary (antidikos = legal opponent) held an advantage she could not match with social connections.</p>',
'4': '<p>"For some time he refused. But finally he said to himself: Even though I don\'t fear God or care what people think..." -- the judge\'s inner monologue reveals his motivations transparently. The self-characterization as someone who neither fears God nor respects humans (ouk entrepomenos anthropon = not turning in shame before people = shameless) is his own assessment, not the narrator\'s label. His eventual capitulation is not a moral transformation but a calculation of self-interest: the widow\'s persistence has become more costly than granting her request.</p>',
'5': '<p>"Yet because this widow keeps bothering me, I will see that she gets justice, so that she won\'t eventually come and attack me!" -- kopiazein (wearing out/exhausting) in papyri sometimes means physical assault; hina m&#275; eis telos erchomen&#275; hypopi&#275;z&#275; me = "lest finally coming she give me a black eye" (hypopi&#257;z&#333; = to strike under the eye, used in boxing). The judge fears either physical confrontation or, more likely, the exhausting social damage of her persistent public complaint. His self-interest (not justice) is his motive -- which makes the kal vachomer all the more forceful.</p>',
'6': '<p>"Listen to what the unjust judge says" -- Jesus draws the congregation\'s attention specifically to the judge\'s own words. The unjust judge (ho krit&#275;s t&#275;s adikias) is explicitly labeled to establish the contrast: the point of the parable depends on the maximum distance between the judge and God. A corrupt, godless, shameless judge who eventually grants justice for self-interested reasons is the least favorable imaginable human authority. If even he responds to persistence, how much more will a just, loving, attentive Father respond to his children?</p>',
'7': '<p>"And will not God bring about justice for his chosen ones, who cry out to him day and night? Will he keep putting them off?" -- the ekdik&#275;sis (justice/vindication/vengeance) of the chosen ones refers to the eschatological vindication of the persecuted community. The term eklektoi (chosen ones) is the LXX and early Jewish term for the covenant community (Isa 42:1; 43:20; 65:9, 15, 22; 1 Chr 16:13; Ps 105:43). The question "will he keep putting them off?" (makrothymei ep\' autois = is he patient/slow over them?) frames the apparent delay of justice as the real test of faith -- not God\'s indifference but his patience allowing time for repentance.</p>',
'8': '<p>"I tell you, he will see that they get justice, and quickly. However, when the Son of Man comes, will he find faith on the earth?" -- the parousia question ends the pericope with eschatological urgency: the issue is not whether God will act (he will, quickly: en tachei) but whether the community will maintain persistent faith-prayer until he does. The question "will he find faith?" (ara heur&#275;sei t&#275;n pistin = will he find the faith?) with the definite article (t&#275;n pistin = the faith, the specific faith just described) asks whether this persistent, trusting prayer -- the faith of the widow -- will characterize the end-time community.</p>',
'9': '<p>The parable of the Pharisee and tax collector is introduced with its target audience: "To some who were confident of their own righteousness and looked down on everyone else" (tois pepoithosi eph\' heautois hoti eisin dikaioi kai exouthenountas tous loipous = those who trusted in themselves that they were righteous and who treated others with contempt). The pepoithosi (perfect participle of peithō = to trust, convince, have confidence) points to a self-assurance that may have begun as genuine piety but has calcified into self-congratulation. The contrast is the prayer postures of two known social types in the first-century Jewish world.</p>',
'10': '<p>The temple was the appointed location for prayer (1 Kgs 8:33-34, 38-39, 42, 48; Dan 6:10: "three times a day he got down on his knees and prayed, giving thanks to his God, just as he had done before"). The set times of prayer (shacharit = morning, minha = afternoon, arvit = evening) brought worshippers to the temple courts. The Pharisee and the tax collector both go to the temple to pray, establishing them both as Jews engaged in religious observance. The contrast is not religious vs. secular but two different orientations within the same religious practice.</p>',
'11': '<p>The Pharisee "stood and prayed about himself" (stath&#275;is pros heauton tauta pros&#275;ucheto = standing, prayed these things to/about himself). The phrase pros heauton is ambiguous: "prayed to himself" (monologue rather than prayer) or "prayed about himself" (content focused on himself). Either reading points to the same issue: the prayer is self-referential, not God-directed. "God, I thank you that I am not like other people -- robbers, evildoers, adulterers -- or even like this tax collector." The gratitude formula (eucharistō soi = I give thanks to you) is appropriate prayer language, but the content expresses comparative righteousness rather than genuine thanksgiving.</p>',
'12': '<p>"I fast twice a week and give a tenth of all I get" -- the Pharisee\'s claims are accurate and represent genuine piety. Twice-weekly fasting (Monday and Thursday, the market days when most people would see the fasting) exceeded the single biblical mandate (Day of Atonement). Tithing "all I get" (panta hosa ktōmai = everything I acquire) went beyond the biblical requirement (which applied to agricultural produce, Deut 14:22-23) to include any income. These are not hypocritical claims; the Pharisee actually does these things. The problem is the orientation: these deeds are presented to God as evidence of superiority rather than gratitude.</p>',
'13': '<p>The tax collector "stood at a distance" (makrothen hest&#333;s) -- the opposite of the Pharisee\'s position of confidence near the temple. The full prayer posture: "would not even look up to heaven, but beat his breast and said, \'God, have mercy on me, a sinner!\'" The downward gaze (refusing to look up toward heaven = toward God) and the breast-beating (typtōn to st&#275;thos autou = striking his chest -- the gesture of grief and contrition, cf. 23:48) express the physical embodiment of humility. "God, have mercy on me, a sinner" (ho theos, hilas&#333;theti moi t&#333; hamart&#333;l&#333;) -- hilas&#333;theti is the Lxx word for divine propitiation (the cover of the ark in Lev 16:15; Ps 51:1). The prayer asks for God\'s atoning mercy, not God\'s recognition of merit.</p>',
'14': '<p>"I tell you that this man, rather than the other, went home justified before God" -- dedikaiōmenos (justified, declared righteous) is the language of the law court: the judge\'s verdict that the accused person is in right standing. In Pauline theology (Rom 3:24-26; Gal 2:16-17), this term carries the weight of the Reformation doctrine of justification by faith. Luke\'s usage here is pre-Pauline: Jesus declares the tax collector justified by God\'s mercy while the Pharisee is not, because the tax collector approached God on the basis of need and the Pharisee on the basis of merit. "For all those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted" -- the reversal maxim appears at 14:11 in the context of table manners; here it applies to prayer.</p>',
'15': '<p>People were bringing infants (breph&#275; = newborns or very young children -- a stronger word than paidia = children, used in Mark 10:13; Matt 19:13) to Jesus for him to touch. The rabbinic tradition of having great teachers touch or bless children is attested: scholars would bring children to outstanding teachers on the Day of Atonement and Sabbath to touch them (b. Kiddushin 32b). The disciples\' rebuke (epitimān = to rebuke, the same word used for demon-rebuking) reveals their understanding that Jesus\' time and attention were for serious adult matters, not infants.</p>',
'16': '<p>"Let the little children come to me, and do not hinder them, for the kingdom of God belongs to such as these" -- the "belonging" of the kingdom to children (t&#333;n gar toioutōn estin h&#275; basileia tou theou = for of such is the kingdom of God) is not about children\'s innocence (a Romantic notion absent from ancient culture) but about their social status and their receptive posture. Children in the ancient world were legally and socially dependent, without status or claim. The kingdom belongs to those who come as dependent recipients, not as deserving claimants. The immediately preceding parable about the justified tax collector makes this point explicit.</p>',
'17': '<p>"Truly I tell you, anyone who will not receive the kingdom of God like a little child will never enter it" -- the kingdom-reception posture (d&#275;xhtai = receive, accept, welcome) of a child is the model. A child receives a gift without a claim to deserve it; a child acknowledges dependence; a child cannot reciprocate. These are not virtues the child has cultivated but social realities of the child\'s position. The adult must adopt the posture of the child before the kingdom: receiving rather than earning, dependent rather than self-sufficient. This connects to the tax collector\'s prayer (v.13) -- both the child and the tax collector approach as recipients, not deservers.</p>',
'18': '<p>A "certain ruler" (archōn tis) asks about inheriting eternal life. In Jewish expectation, inheriting eternal life (or "the world to come," Heb. olam ha-ba) was the hope of the righteous. The ruler\'s title archon (ruler, official) may indicate a synagogue official or a member of the local governing council. He addresses Jesus as "Good Teacher" (Didaskale agathe) -- an unusual form of address that Jesus questions: "Why do you call me good?" No one is good except God alone -- a statement that invites the ruler to consider what his address implies about Jesus\' identity, or that distinguishes absolute goodness (God\'s) from derived goodness (human).</p>',
'19': '<p>"Why do you call me good? No one is good -- except God alone" -- the question is not a denial of Jesus\' goodness or deity but an invitation to deeper reflection. If Jesus alone is truly good, and goodness belongs to God alone, what does that imply about Jesus? The ruler has addressed Jesus with a title appropriate to God without recognizing what he is saying. The Markan version (10:18) is identical; Matthew 19:17 modifies slightly to "Why do you ask me about what is good?" -- a textual variant that removes the theological sharpness of the exchange.</p>',
'20': '<p>Jesus cites commandments from the second table of the Decalogue (Exod 20:12-16; Deut 5:16-20) -- those governing human relationships rather than the first table\'s commands about relationship with God. The specific selection (adultery, murder, stealing, false witness, honoring parents) follows Deut 5 order, making the ruler\'s claim to have kept them from youth ("apo neotes" = from youth/adolescence) plausible: these are the commandments a law-observant Jew would indeed keep. The absence of the commandments against coveting (Deut 5:21) is significant: the ruler\'s failure is precisely at the point of covetousness, as v.22 will reveal.</p>',
'21': '<p>"All these I have kept since I was a boy" (panta tauta ephylaza ek neotes) -- the ruler\'s claim is sincere, not hypocritical. Paul makes a similar claim about his pre-conversion life (Phil 3:6: "as for legalistic righteousness, faultless"). Within the framework of Jewish observance, a carefully law-observant person could genuinely claim to have kept the social commandments. The ruler is not lying; he has been a model Jew by the standards of his community. This makes the "one thing lacking" all the more surprising: the problem is not gross sin but a subtle, structural attachment.</p>',
'22': '<p>"Sell everything you have and give to the poor, and you will have treasure in heaven. Then come, follow me" -- the instruction is unique in Jesus\' teaching: he does not give this command universally but specifically to this man at this moment. The instruction identifies the precise point where the ruler\'s otherwise complete obedience fails: his wealth is his actual security and identity, not God. "Treasure in heaven" (th&#275;sauron en ouranois = heavenly treasury) reflects the Jewish concept of the treasury of merits stored before God (m. Peah 1:1; Tob 4:9: "almsgiving delivers from death and will purge away every sin"). The poverty-redistribution prescription (sell everything, give to the poor) is the specific cure for his specific idolatry.</p>',
'23': '<p>"When he heard this, he became very sad, because he was very wealthy" -- perilypos (very sad/sorrowful) reflects genuine anguish, not mere annoyance. The man is confronted with a real loss. "Very wealthy" (plousios sfodra = extremely/intensely wealthy) establishes that the cost is enormous. Luke\'s consistent teaching about wealth as spiritual danger (6:24; 12:16-21; 16:19-31) reaches its clearest confrontation here: the rich man\'s sadness is the accurate emotional response to discovering that his wealth is the idol that stands between him and eternal life.</p>',
'24': '<p>"How hard it is for the rich to enter the kingdom of God!" -- Jesus\' comment to the watching crowd reframes the individual encounter as a general principle. Dyskolos (with difficulty/hard) is a comparative: the rich person faces a particular structural obstacle to kingdom entry that the poor do not. The wealth itself is the obstacle: it creates the illusion of self-sufficiency, provides an alternative security, and demands the loyalty that belongs to God. This is not about moral failings of the rich but about the soteriological structure of wealth as a competing trust-object.</p>',
'25': '<p>"Indeed, it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for someone who is rich to enter the kingdom of God" -- the camel-through-a-needle\'s-eye saying is one of the most memorable hyperboles in the Gospels. Various attempts to soften it (the "Needle Gate" theory, or reading kamelos as rope/cable rather than camel) have no early support. The image is deliberately impossible: the largest animal familiar to Palestinian audiences squeezed through the smallest of openings. The hyperbole makes the point forcefully: natural, unaided entry of the wealthy into the kingdom is impossible. Salvation must come from outside the wealthy person\'s own resources.</p>',
'26': '<p>"Who then can be saved?" -- the disciples\' question reflects the common assumption that wealth was a sign of divine blessing and the wealthy were therefore more likely to be saved. In Deut 28-30, covenant obedience was promised to result in prosperity; the wealthy could therefore appear to be the most visibly blessed. If the wealthy cannot easily enter the kingdom, the implied conclusion is that no one can -- the most outwardly blessed face the most difficulty. The question reveals the disciples\' underlying prosperity-theology assumption.</p>',
'27': '<p>"What is impossible with man is possible with God" -- Jesus\' answer does not soften the statement about wealth but escalates it. Human impossibility (the camel) becomes divine possibility. The salvation of the wealthy is not achieved by effort or generosity but only by divine action that transforms the person\'s attachment to wealth. Abraham was wealthy (Gen 13:2); Zacchaeus was wealthy (19:2-9) and was saved; the principle is not that wealth automatically prevents salvation but that only God can break the hold that wealth has on the human heart.</p>',
'28': '<p>"We have left all we had to follow you" -- Peter\'s statement parallels the ruler\'s lack: the disciples had done what the ruler was unwilling to do. "Left all" (aphentes ta idia = leaving our own things) echoes the language of the disciple-calls (5:11, 28). The implicit question is: what do we receive in return? This is not mercenary calculation but the recognition that radical sacrifice invites a corresponding promise. Peter\'s statement functions as both a claim and a question: we have done this -- what can we expect?</p>',
'29': '<p>"Truly I tell you, no one who has left home or wife or brothers or parents or children for the sake of the kingdom of God will fail to receive many times as much in this age" -- the promise of hundredfold return (Mark 10:30: "a hundred times as much in this present age") is reframed by Luke as "many times as much" (pollaplasiōna) without the specific number. The "this age" dimension is significant: the return is not deferred entirely to the future but begins in the present community, where the followers of Jesus receive home, family, and belonging in the new household of the Kingdom. Acts 2:44-45 and 4:32-35 show this communal provision in practice.</p>',
'30': '<p>"And in the age to come, eternal life" -- the two-age framework (this age / the age to come) is standard Second Temple Jewish eschatology (Heb. olam ha-zeh / olam ha-ba), appearing in the Mishnah (m. Avot 2:7; 4:1) and throughout rabbinic literature. "Eternal life" (z&#333;&#275;n ai&#333;nion = life of the age, the life that belongs to the coming age) is the qualitative life of God\'s kingdom, not merely endless duration. The ruler asked about "inheriting" eternal life (v.18); Jesus promises it as the ultimate reward of kingdom-oriented renunciation.</p>',
'31': '<p>"Jesus took the Twelve aside and told them, \'We are going up to Jerusalem, and everything that is written by the prophets about the Son of Man will be fulfilled\'" -- the third and most explicit passion prediction in Luke (cf. 9:22, 44). "Everything that is written by the prophets" frames the passion as scriptural fulfillment (cf. 24:25-27, 44-46 where the risen Jesus interprets the suffering as the fulfillment of "Moses and all the Prophets"). The Servant songs of Isaiah (42; 49; 50; 52:13-53:12), Psalm 22, and Zechariah 9-13 are the primary prophetic texts the passion narratives fulfill.</p>',
'32': '<p>"He will be delivered over to the Gentiles. They will mock him, insult him, spit on him, flog him and kill him" -- the specificity of the passion prediction increases with each iteration. The progressive revelations anticipate Luke\'s passion narrative detail: mockery (22:63-65), flogging (23:16, 22), death (23:46). "Delivered over to the Gentiles" (paradoth&#275;setai tois ethnesin) anticipates the transfer from Jewish authority to Roman authority (23:1-25), with paradid&#333;mi (hand over/betray) echoing the Judas betrayal throughout the passion.</p>',
'33': '<p>"On the third day he will rise again" -- the third-day resurrection is the consistent element across all three Synoptic passion predictions (9:22; 9:44 implicit; 18:33 explicit). The "third day" reflects both the OT pattern (Hos 6:2: "After two days he will revive us; on the third day he will restore us"; Jonah 1:17: three days in the fish; Gen 22:4: the third day Abraham sees the place of sacrifice) and the fundamental resurrection kerygma (1 Cor 15:4: "he was raised on the third day according to the Scriptures").</p>',
'34': '<p>"The disciples did not understand any of this. Its meaning was hidden from them, and they did not know what he was saying" -- Luke\'s threefold statement of incomprehension (ouk synekan, kekrymmenos apo aut&#333;n, ouk egindskōn) is the most emphatic in the Synoptics. The passive "was hidden" (kekrymmenos) implies divine concealment -- a motif in the Hebrew prophetic tradition where the full meaning of prophecy is sealed until the moment of fulfillment (Dan 12:4, 9: "seal up the words"; cf. Luke 24:45: Jesus "opened their minds so they could understand the Scriptures"). The disciples will understand only after the resurrection (24:8, 44-45).</p>',
'35': '<p>The healing of Bartimaeus (unnamed in Luke, named in Mark 10:46) occurs "as Jesus approached Jericho" -- Luke places the healing before the Zacchaeus encounter in Jericho (19:1-10), while Mark and Matthew place it as Jesus is leaving Jericho. The differences may reflect different Jericho locations (old Jericho vs. Herodian Jericho are 2 km apart) or different narrative ordering. Old Testament Jericho (Tell es-Sultan) and Herodian Jericho (Wadi Qelt) were distinct sites. Jericho was a wealthy city in Jesus\' time, home to Herod\'s winter palace and a prosperous population.</p>',
'36': '<p>The blind man hears a crowd passing by (ochlou diaporeuomenou) and asks what is happening. His isolation from the crowds is the mark of his marginalization: he cannot see to interpret events; he depends on verbal description. The information that "Jesus of Nazareth is passing by" (I&#275;sous ho Naz&#333;raios parerchestai) identifies Jesus by his hometown designation -- the standard way to distinguish individuals of the same name (cf. Acts 2:22; 3:6; 4:10; 6:14; 22:8).</p>',
'37': '<p>The crowd\'s description of Jesus as "Jesus of Nazareth" triggers the blind man\'s use of a different title: "Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!" The title "Son of David" (Huios Dauid) is a messianic designation rooted in the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16; Ps 89:3-4, 29-37; Isa 9:6-7; 11:1-9; Jer 23:5-6; Ezek 34:23-24; Amos 9:11-12). By the first century, "Son of David" was a standard messianic title in Jewish expectation (Psalms of Solomon 17:21-43). The blind man\'s recognition and declaration of this title demonstrates more insight than the sighted crowds who merely know he is from Nazareth.</p>',
'38': '<p>"He called out: \'Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!\'" -- the cry for mercy (ele&#275;son me) uses the same root as the Kyrie eleison prayer and the Lukan parable of the Pharisee and tax collector (18:13: "God, have mercy on me, a sinner"). The blind man\'s cry is a prayer addressed to the messianic king, invoking both the Davidic tradition of God\'s steadfast love (hesed/eleos) and the royal tradition of the king who champions the vulnerable. The insistence despite rebuke (those who led the way rebuked him, v.39) mirrors the persistent widow of 18:1-8 -- another parable of persistent petition just preceding this narrative.</p>',
'39': '<p>"Those who led the way rebuked him and told him to be quiet, but he shouted all the more" -- the rebuke comes not from Jesus\' opponents but from those leading the way for Jesus, presumably disciples or sympathizers. The rebuke (epitiman = rebuke, the same word used for demons and storms) attempts to silence what the rebukers regard as inappropriate or excessive behavior. The blind man\'s response -- shouting all the more -- is the paradigm of persistent prayer in action, paralleling the parables of the widow and the friend at midnight. His desperation overrides social convention.</p>',
'40': '<p>Jesus stopped and ordered the man to be brought to him -- statheis (standing still) in the middle of the Jerusalem-bound journey. This pause in the most significant journey of Jesus\' life (the final approach to Jerusalem) to attend to a single blind beggar enacts the kingdom priority. "Came near, he asked him" (eggisantos de autou ep&#275;rotosen auton) -- Jesus\' approach closes the distance that the blind man\'s marginalization created. The question ("What do you want me to do for you?") is addressed to the man directly -- giving him agency in his own healing.</p>',
'41': '<p>"Lord, I want to see" (Kyrie, hina anableps&#333; = Lord, that I may see again) -- anablepō means literally "to look up again," possibly implying he had once had sight. "Lord" (Kyrie) is the resurrection title applied to the earthly Jesus -- Luke\'s consistent usage in the travel narrative. The simplicity of the request is striking: he does not explain his situation (evident), does not ask for money or position, asks precisely for what he needs. The request receives the same response as the justified tax collector and the returning Samaritan: "your faith has healed/saved you."</p>',
'42': '<p>"Receive your sight; your faith has healed you" (anable pson, h&#275; pistis sou ses&#333;ken se) -- the formula h&#275; pistis sou ses&#333;ken se appears at 7:50 (the sinful woman), 8:48 (the hemorrhaging woman), 17:19 (the Samaritan leper), and 18:42 (Bartimaeus). The healing/salvation is attributed to faith (trust in Jesus as messianic healer/savior) rather than to Jesus\'s power alone -- not because the power is not his but because the access to the power comes through faith. The immediate restoration ("immediately he received his sight") continues the Lukan pattern of instantaneous healing that demonstrates the fullness of divine power.</p>',
'43': '<p>Bartimaeus "followed Jesus, praising God. When all the people saw it, they also praised God" -- the twofold praise (Bartimaeus\'s individual praise and the crowd\'s corporate response) is the Lukan literary conclusion to a healing narrative. "Praising God" (ain&#333;n ton theon = glorifying/praising God) is the community response to divine action throughout Luke (2:20; 5:26; 7:16; 13:13; 17:15; 18:43; 23:47; 24:53). The crowd\'s praise connects individual healing to communal recognition of God\'s presence in Jesus. Bartimaeus\' following of Jesus while praising God frames him as the paradigm disciple: healed, following, praising. He enters Jerusalem with Jesus as one who already confesses him as messianic Son of David.</p>',
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    import json as _json, pathlib as _pl
    inter = _json.loads((_pl.Path(__file__).parent.parent / 'data/interlinear/luke.json').read_text())
    for ch in [17, 18]:
        ck = str(ch)
        have = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        need = set(inter.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = sorted(int(v) for v in (need - have))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(have)}/{len(need)} -- missing: {missing}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
